## ATS Optimization Fundamentals Learned

**What is an ATS (Applicant Tracking System)?**
An ATS is software used by employers to scan, filter, and rank resumes before a human ever reads them. Studies show 75% of resumes are rejected by ATS before reaching a recruiter.

**Key ATS Rules:**
- No photos, images, tables, or text boxes — ATS cannot parse them
- Use standard section headers: Summary, Experience, Education, Skills, Certifications
- Single-column layout — ATS reads left to right, top to bottom
- Standard fonts (Calibri, Arial, Times New Roman)
- Keywords must match the job description exactly
- Dates in consistent format: `Mon YYYY – Mon YYYY`
- Quantify achievements — numbers rank higher than adjectives
- File format: `.docx` or plain `.pdf` (not scanned PDF)

---

## Before vs. After Comparison

| Element | Before (Original) | After (ATS-Optimized) |
|---|---|---|
| **Pages** | 3 pages | 1 page |
| **Photo** | Included | Removed |
| **Layout** | Multi-column sections | Single-column throughout |
| **Section Headers** | "Key Highlights", "Memberships & Fellowships" | Standard: Summary, Experience, Certifications |
| **Keywords** | Buried in body text | Front-loaded in Core Competencies block |
| **Metrics** | Scattered, easy to miss | Prominent in every bullet |
| **Certifications** | 2-column bullet list (ATS unfriendly) | Single-line keyword string |
| **Profile Photo** | Present (can trigger bias filters) | Removed |
| **Older roles** | Fully detailed (Hays, AON Hewitt, 2010–2015) | Condensed — space given to recent high-impact roles |

